So too the land· lord of a house had a tacit hypothec over things ‘invecta and illata,’ as security lor his rent: ‘eo iure utimur, ut quae in praedia urbana inducta illata sunt, pignori esse credantur, quasi id tacite convenerit: ' in rusticis praediis contra observatur‘ Dig. ao. a. 4. pr. : and the lessor of agricultural land had the same implied right over the crops: ‘in praediis rusticis fruetus, qui ibi nascuntur, tacite intelleguntur pignori esse domino lundi locati, etsi nominatim id non convenerit' Dig. ib. 7. pr. Lastly should be noticed the new power ol pledging the same property to several persons in succession, though to do this without notice to prior pledgees rendered the debtor liable to a charge ol stellionatus, Dig. 13. 7. 37. 1. Hence, too, questions ol collision aud priority among competing pledgees, which occupy so large a space in modern Roman law: a subject, however, too wide to be touched upon here.

One result ol the general use ol hypotheca was the extension ol its rules and remedies to pignus. ln the time ol Ulpian the right ol sale had become an essential and inherent part ol every pignus: ‘etsi non convenerit de distrahendo pignore, hoc tamen iure utimur, ut liceat distrahere, si modo non convenit ne liceat. Ubi vero convenitne distraheretur, creditor, si distraxerit, lurti obligatur, nisi ei ter luerit denuntiatum ut solvat, et cessaverit’ Dig. 13. 7. 4. The remedies again were the same, whether the pledge was effected by pignus or hypotheca: so that in Justinian's time (as he remarks, Bk. iv. 6. 7 int), there was hutone surviving point ol difference between them: il possession ol the object pledged passed to the creditor, it was called pignus, il not, hypotheca; cl. Dig. ao. 1. 5. 1 (Marcianus): ‘inter' pignus et hypothecam tanturn nominis sonus differt!
